Opinions

Need for welfare reform

Besides health care and Haiti, one of the most discussed

political issues this year, by both the president and Congress,’

is the need for welfare reform.

The American welfare system is one of the most inefficient
and counter-productive programs ever implemented by any
nation. The objective of the welfare system, developed in the
1960s during the Johnson administration, was to provide a
safety net for people undergoing temporary economic hard-

ship and to aid them in re—integrating into society. Instead it
has done the exact opposite.

The welfare system has created a dependent society. One
gets greater economic benefits, mainly via Medicaid, from
staying on welfare than from going out and getting an entry-
level, minimum wage job. A system which actively promotes
non-working individuals is suicidal for a society. Yet this is
exactly the system which we currently have.

Furthermore, the welfare system self-perpetuates itself.
Studies have shown that children born into dependent families
are far more likely to become dependent on welfare them-
selves. This creates a cycle of dependency, which is especially
harmful since the poor sector is by far the fastest growing seg-
ment of our population. Therefore, the number and percentage
of people living below the poverty line and dependent on the
government steadily increases.

This nation was founded on a strong work ethic. John
Smith’s motto of “work or die,” set the standard for many gen-
erations of Americans. However, the American work ethic is
now dismal. Individuals look more and more to the govern-
ment and others to provide their needs for them, rather than
supplying those needs themselves. The welfare system is an
endemic example of a greater problem which faces this coun-
try as we move towards the 2lst century.

However, the problems created by the welfare system can be
rectified and without too much difficulty. Unfortunately, the
system is so entrenched that simply doing away with it would
probably create chaos, but a gradual phasing out could be fair-
ly easily accomplished if Congress and the president could
only regenerate their own work ethics and pass substantial
reform.

Some of the proposals currently on the table involve placing
a limit on welfare benefits of two years. This would accom-
plish many things. First, it would disrupt the cycle of
dependency, because after two years, that’s it, you’re on your
own. Also it would aid in the reintegration of individuals
into society, as there would be a far greater incentive for one to
get a job since one could only receive benefits for a limited
period. ‘ A

It is not the role of the government to provide for the liveli-
hood of its citizens, which effectively means the majority pays
for the laziness of the indigent minority. A national aid system
which promotes work (“workfare” rather than welfare) is in
the best interests of all of society.

