I was inspired to write this
column by a letter to The Pitt
News in which the respondent
unfairly criticized a June col-
umn of mine on racism. I
won’t respond directly to that
letter here, but I would like to
put forward some thoughts on
the notion of power vis-a-vis
true justice. Two truisms
come to mind. .

r _I) You cannot gain justice

by pursuing power. The

notion that justice can be
obtained by placing certain
people in positions of authori-
ty has no basis in fact. That’s
why revolutionaries and radi-
cals are rarely taken seriously,
especially in a self-centered
society such as ours.

Back in 1984, a group of
Lutheran pastors and unem-
ployed steelworkers known
respectively as the
Denominational Ministry

