disrupted the later Easter
Sunday service at my church.
They chose my church amid
accusations that members of
the congregation who were in
the steel companies’ upper
management put them out of
work and were breaking their
union. One of the demands
the groups made was to take
the church’s entire endow-
ment — about $6 million.
Well, they demonstrated for
about three years but failed to

rally support for the cause. ’

Why? Because they wanted
power, not justice. That’s the
same reason that black
nationalists, the “religious
right” and Operation Rescue,
among others, have similarly
fallen short of their goals and
will continue to do so.

In fact, the desire for power
is at the root of all of the
human race’s social ills. Illicit
sex? Sure. Racism? It fits.
Gang violence? Robbery?
The S&L scandals? Right
there. And if I needed any
more confirmation, I went
back to the Biblical story of
Adam and Eve, and with what
did the serpent successfully
tempt them? The idea that
“you will be as gods, know-
ing good and evil.” And the
trouble with power is, as I
have said before, that the
desire for such is insatiable;
for that reason, seeking power
inevitably becomes the end
rather than the means. Former
Watergate conspirator Chuck
Colson. confessed in his book
Loving God that “the more
power I acquired, the more
power acquired me.”

Furthermore, power can
never be simply taken —— it
must be conferred, given or
even won. No leader is worth
anything without followers,
and he or she must be willing
to say what. at the very least,
people want to hear. (Rush
Limbaugh comes to mind at

power

this point). As a Pitt News
columnist and radio commen-
tator, I have a certain amount
of power awarded to me, but
if I write or speak about
things without proof, I run the
risk of forfeiting my audi-
ence.

2) You cannot pursue jus-
tice without building relation-
ships. Justice for one neces-
sarily means justice for all.
One reason such‘ radical
groups fail to cause change is
because of their inability to
relate to anyone else outside
their sphere of influence -
they foolishly think that they
will prevail because of sheer
“moral force.” On the other
hand, the early Christians,
who had no political power to
speak of in ancient Rome,
outlived what was then the
most powerful empire in the
world simply by sharing their
“good news” with whomever
they came into contact. In the
Philippines, the people chased
dictator Ferdinand Marcos by
similarly reaching the Filipino
military, Marcos’ power base.
_ Again, justice never occurs
in a vacuum. For example,
you cannot seek justice for
blacks without seeking justice
for whites, as racism affects
both profoundly. Sexism traps
both men and women in its
snare; any solution must con-
sider both sides. Those who
claim religious bigotry need
to come into relationship with
their “God-rejecting” foes to
see what needs to be done. ,

You might get power by
striving for justice, but not the
other way around, and unless
and until people learn that,
the evils that they attack will
be just as intransigent as they
ever were. There is a formula:
Love leads to justice, with
power the side effect. That’s
the ultimate goal.

Nothing else comes close.

